64
00:03:50,869 --> 00:03:51,710
Half... whatever.

65
00:03:51,730 --> 00:03:53,590
You know, I'm going to split the room right down the middle,

66
00:03:53,970 --> 00:03:56,811
because, you know, for every fallout...

67
00:03:58,387 --> 00:04:01,270
as a Final Fantasy, whatever fucking number they're up to.

68
00:04:01,310 --> 00:04:03,292
For every portal, there's an Uncharted 2, right?

69
00:04:03,712 --> 00:04:08,417
In both cases, there's very different approaches to player identity.

70
00:04:09,278 --> 00:04:12,361
So what I'm going to try to do here is dig up the commonalities,

71
00:04:12,481 --> 00:04:15,685
like, unearth the foundation that these games are based on,

72
00:04:16,145 --> 00:04:19,068
and try to reconcile those different identity approaches

73
00:04:19,108 --> 00:04:21,531
into something that hopefully we can use as a framework.

74
00:04:22,357 --> 00:04:23,797
So I'm going to do this in five parts.

75
00:04:23,958 --> 00:04:26,639
In part one, I'm going to establish an identity range.

76
00:04:26,719 --> 00:04:29,461
It's going to be this graph that captures both extremes of how

77
00:04:29,501 --> 00:04:31,762
we may choose to offer player identity.

78
00:04:32,702 --> 00:04:34,343
And part two is going to look at double consciousness,

79
00:04:34,403 --> 00:04:37,625
understanding it and seeing why it makes writing for games

80
00:04:37,685 --> 00:04:39,727
different from other media, and then hopefully using

81
00:04:39,767 --> 00:04:41,608
that knowledge to create some good player identity.

82
00:04:41,628 --> 00:04:43,829
And that's what part three is going to be about.

83
00:04:43,869 --> 00:04:46,330
I have three specific examples, kind of showing you

84
00:04:46,370 --> 00:04:47,451
how we can use those lessons.

85
00:04:47,913 --> 00:04:53,139
And then part four, which is actually wedged into part three, because it kind of flows in there, is about myth reinforcement.

86
00:04:53,579 --> 00:04:56,803
What it means and how we can use it to make better stories.

87
00:04:57,144 --> 00:05:01,088
And then part five is going to be takeaway, and we're going to see if we can learn some lessons from all of this.

88
00:05:02,750 --> 00:05:08,157
So we're going to talk, we're going to start by talking about identity approaches, and to do that we should talk about avatars.

89
00:05:11,783 --> 00:05:14,725
So I think we all know that we use avatars to enter a game world, right?

90
00:05:14,745 --> 00:05:18,586
And it's usually an abstract concept, but Ultima, the beauty of Ultima was that

91
00:05:19,007 --> 00:05:24,169
it's actually an awesome example of exactly how this school of thought looks at the player-avatar relationship, right?

92
00:05:25,029 --> 00:05:30,792
Rules of Play has a definition for this, and it describes the avatar and its identity approach as, quote,

93
00:05:31,352 --> 00:05:35,153
a puppet, an object for the player to manipulate according to the rules of the game.

94
00:05:35,682 --> 00:05:37,422
I think we all easily understand what that means.

95
00:05:37,522 --> 00:05:40,002
We treat the avatar as a lifeless puppet,

96
00:05:40,102 --> 00:05:41,743
as our extension into the world,

97
00:05:41,783 --> 00:05:43,683
and then we project ourselves onto this puppet.

98
00:05:44,123 --> 00:05:46,764
Puppet doesn't have any character traits

99
00:05:46,804 --> 00:05:47,804
or opinions of its own.

100
00:05:47,884 --> 00:05:49,304
It's literally that of the player.

101
00:05:50,284 --> 00:05:51,865
So this analogy works really good

102
00:05:52,065 --> 00:05:54,185
for games with weakly defined characters, right?

103
00:05:54,365 --> 00:05:56,885
And usually these games put a really high premium

104
00:05:57,025 --> 00:05:58,986
on high agency and on the player's story.

105
00:05:59,706 --> 00:06:00,826
So in my identity range,

106
00:06:00,966 --> 00:06:02,907
I'm gonna put it on the left side right over there.

107
00:06:03,893 --> 00:06:07,677
And while this is a very common approach to player identity, especially early on,

108
00:06:07,777 --> 00:06:09,778
this doesn't tell the whole story, right?

109
00:06:09,839 --> 00:06:12,601
Especially recently, there's this exactly opposite approach,

110
00:06:12,621 --> 00:06:16,024
where we use strongly characterized, fully fleshed-out avatars

111
00:06:16,064 --> 00:06:19,767
who have their own motivation and their own backstory, like Nathan Drake, right?

112
00:06:19,807 --> 00:06:22,289
I mean, he's not really a puppet. Yes, every so often I play him,

113
00:06:22,309 --> 00:06:26,453
but he talks, he sets directions, he adds some cutscenes, he goes after the girl,

114
00:06:26,653 --> 00:06:29,555
a lot of stuff that I, as the player, don't actually affect.

115
00:06:30,117 --> 00:06:34,758
So that's a completely different approach to authoring player identity, and we need to understand that one as well.

116
00:06:35,398 --> 00:06:41,180
So a great metaphor I have found for this approach comes from Nick Montfort, and it's from this essay,

117
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:44,961
Threading the Player Character, and it was published in this book, Second Person.

118
00:06:45,481 --> 00:06:49,722
So what Nick Montfort is saying is that the player is steering the avatar like, quote,

119
00:06:50,342 --> 00:06:53,923
a sort of vehicle from which the world can be seen and otherwise experienced.

120
00:06:54,563 --> 00:06:57,483
This character both constrains us, we have to remain in the vehicle.

121
00:06:57,846 --> 00:06:59,426
and also opens up possibilities.

122
00:06:59,666 --> 00:07:02,247
We can use the vehicle to get around and even affect changes

123
00:07:02,287 --> 00:07:02,687
in the world.

124
00:07:03,748 --> 00:07:05,368
So what I love about this analogy

125
00:07:05,428 --> 00:07:07,549
is that it completely visualizes how

126
00:07:07,569 --> 00:07:09,809
an active cinematic experience like Unshutter 2 works.

127
00:07:10,329 --> 00:07:12,050
Unshutter 2 is very strongly structured.

128
00:07:12,110 --> 00:07:14,290
It's locking the player into this very specific story

129
00:07:14,310 --> 00:07:14,711
progression.

130
00:07:15,271 --> 00:07:17,791
So if we visualize the structure as a road network, which

131
00:07:17,851 --> 00:07:20,272
is connected by tunnels, which of course represents

132
00:07:20,332 --> 00:07:22,393
the story cut scenes and the structural points that

133
00:07:22,413 --> 00:07:24,193
structure the experience, we can see

134
00:07:24,213 --> 00:07:25,994
that we're driving Nathan Drake across the road.

135
00:07:26,194 --> 00:07:27,274
That's him driving right there.

136
00:07:27,847 --> 00:07:30,368
And it shows us that there is some choice and expression

137
00:07:30,388 --> 00:07:32,869
that we have during play, but it also shows us the limitations.

138
00:07:33,349 --> 00:07:35,910
We cannot drive off the map in whatever direction we choose to.

139
00:07:36,590 --> 00:07:37,991
And our progression is predetermined.

140
00:07:38,011 --> 00:07:40,271
It's always gated by these tunnels, which connect

141
00:07:40,412 --> 00:07:41,312
each piece of the road.

142
00:07:42,432 --> 00:07:43,773
So in our identity range, we're going

143
00:07:43,793 --> 00:07:46,974
to put vehicles on the opposite side right here.

144
00:07:47,074 --> 00:07:49,195
And I think these are two really good cornerstones

145
00:07:49,235 --> 00:07:50,055
to anchor our spectrum.

146
00:07:54,914 --> 00:07:58,356
So regardless of how we look at it, if it's the player exerting his will on a puppet,

147
00:07:58,376 --> 00:08:00,817
or if it's a player driving a vehicle through an experience,

148
00:08:01,238 --> 00:08:05,340
the one thing we have to always keep in mind is that player and avatar always remain separate entities.

149
00:08:05,500 --> 00:08:07,861
This is something that Rules of Play calls double consciousness.

150
00:08:07,962 --> 00:08:11,383
It's this idea that players, even when they're fully immersed in an experience,

151
00:08:11,424 --> 00:08:13,405
are always aware of the fact that they're playing a game.

152
00:08:13,565 --> 00:08:17,827
And that in playing a character, they're always manipulating an artificial construct.

153
00:08:18,648 --> 00:08:19,968
So what's interesting about this is...

154
00:08:20,398 --> 00:08:22,900
that the player himself establishes this double consciousness, right?

155
00:08:22,940 --> 00:08:25,582
Because he makes the choice to enter the magic circle of the game.

156
00:08:26,082 --> 00:08:30,905
He chooses to push aside parts of his identity that will prevent him from enjoying or acting

157
00:08:30,945 --> 00:08:32,446
appropriately within the game.

158
00:08:32,886 --> 00:08:37,369
So in a way, the player willingly turns himself into a schizophrenic, and he willingly submits

159
00:08:37,409 --> 00:08:41,351
himself to all these different voices, which different points of views and different agendas

160
00:08:41,391 --> 00:08:42,792
which are all whispering inside his head.

161
00:08:43,613 --> 00:08:45,294
So this is probably the key to this topic.

162
00:08:45,394 --> 00:08:48,516
As game writers and game designers, we need to understand double consciousness.

163
00:08:48,536 --> 00:08:49,336
And

164
00:08:49,356 --> 00:08:49,557
that's it.

165
00:08:50,858 --> 00:08:54,661
This knowledge is out there, it's in multiple books, it's in multiple GDC talks.

166
00:08:54,981 --> 00:08:59,385
The reason, I think, why we still don't really seem to have an institutionalized knowledge

167
00:08:59,665 --> 00:09:02,928
in this industry is because it's a little bit difficult to understand.

168
00:09:03,088 --> 00:09:06,851
Because double consciousness is multi-layered, it's kind of like a dream within a dream within

169
00:09:06,891 --> 00:09:07,232
a dream.

170
00:09:07,892 --> 00:09:12,056
And even in this lecture, we have to drill down into the concept not once, but twice.

171
00:09:14,458 --> 00:09:16,480
So if we dig deeper into double consciousness once...

172
00:09:19,036 --> 00:09:21,317
we get to Gary Fine and the book Shared Fantasy.

173
00:09:21,858 --> 00:09:23,699
So this was a book that was written, I think, even in the 70s.

174
00:09:23,799 --> 00:09:26,801
It's about real-life tabletop RPG groups,

175
00:09:27,081 --> 00:09:28,702
but it applies to digital games as well.

176
00:09:29,443 --> 00:09:31,404
And Gary Fine splits double consciousness,

177
00:09:31,544 --> 00:09:33,345
well, the chronology is wrong here,

178
00:09:33,385 --> 00:09:35,206
but we can say he splits double consciousness

179
00:09:35,246 --> 00:09:36,767
into three parts of identity

180
00:09:37,248 --> 00:09:39,129
that players experience when they're playing a game.

181
00:09:39,309 --> 00:09:40,150
So we have the character.

182
00:09:40,750 --> 00:09:43,192
This is the fictional character embodied by the player,

183
00:09:43,252 --> 00:09:45,813
you know, Ogre, the dwarf, or whoever he chooses to play.

184
00:09:46,354 --> 00:09:47,154
Then we have the player.

185
00:09:47,194 --> 00:09:48,755
So this is the player himself.

186
00:09:49,440 --> 00:09:53,223
acting within and exploring the framework and the rules of the games, like rolling dice,

187
00:09:53,383 --> 00:09:55,924
and, you know, actually understanding the rules and using them.

188
00:09:56,504 --> 00:09:57,565
Then we also have the person.

189
00:09:58,085 --> 00:10:00,046
And this is the player as a person with life demands,

190
00:10:00,227 --> 00:10:02,508
which we push aside while we're playing, right?

191
00:10:02,528 --> 00:10:04,949
We're trying to immerse ourselves in Ogre or the Dwarf or whatever.

192
00:10:05,510 --> 00:10:09,092
But they're never forgotten, because if I have to leave at 6pm and have to catch a train,

193
00:10:09,132 --> 00:10:11,253
that's always going to be somewhere on the back of my conscious.

194
00:10:14,882 --> 00:10:17,082
there's this inherent ambiguity here, right?

195
00:10:17,163 --> 00:10:19,003
On the one hand, we have the player actual,

196
00:10:19,023 --> 00:10:21,204
the way we usually talk about the player and what he does,

197
00:10:21,244 --> 00:10:23,225
but you also have this identity frame player.

198
00:10:23,805 --> 00:10:26,166
So what I'm gonna try to do for the rest of this talk

199
00:10:26,186 --> 00:10:28,227
to avoid ambiguity is to,

200
00:10:29,307 --> 00:10:31,368
what call Gary finds identity part the player,

201
00:10:31,508 --> 00:10:33,429
and whenever I'm talking about the player actual,

202
00:10:33,529 --> 00:10:34,930
I'm gonna try to call him gamer.

203
00:10:35,050 --> 00:10:36,430
So we have a distinction right there.

204
00:10:36,770 --> 00:10:38,331
But see how well I succeed,

205
00:10:38,371 --> 00:10:40,352
because this is totally ingrained in me as well,

206
00:10:40,572 --> 00:10:41,252
like saying player.

207
00:10:42,095 --> 00:10:44,016
So in psychology, I guess, we call these frames.

208
00:10:44,176 --> 00:10:46,959
It's the character frame, the player frame, and the person frame.

209
00:10:47,399 --> 00:10:51,122
And these are those schizophrenia-induced voices that I was talking about,

210
00:10:51,162 --> 00:10:52,843
which are whispering to the player inside his head.

211
00:10:53,344 --> 00:10:55,906
These are voices that want to be satisfied, they have their own goals,

212
00:10:55,926 --> 00:10:57,047
they have their own motivations.

213
00:10:58,208 --> 00:11:01,130
And if you want to know how to motivate somebody, how to keep them satisfied,

214
00:11:01,891 --> 00:11:03,732
we need to know what defines them, right?

215
00:11:04,032 --> 00:11:05,253
How we actually hook into them.

216
00:11:06,514 --> 00:11:09,217
So this is where we drill one level deeper into double consciousness,

217
00:11:09,977 --> 00:11:11,418
and where it gets a little bit weird.

