240
00:12:10,033 --> 00:12:12,995
And he might be based on a literary, pop, or mythic archetype.

241
00:12:13,355 --> 00:12:17,138
Then we have the player, and this is the player himself solving problems and completing tasks.

242
00:12:17,198 --> 00:12:19,159
So this talks about moment-to-moment gameplay, right?

243
00:12:19,179 --> 00:12:20,520
Really tight motivational loops.

244
00:12:21,221 --> 00:12:23,623
Pure games, pretty much, the reason why we start playing them.

245
00:12:24,103 --> 00:12:26,705
And we have the player with a sense of skill level and reputation.

246
00:12:27,065 --> 00:12:31,909
And I'm using this to kind of map his sense of mastery and his progress as he's going through the game.

247
00:12:32,349 --> 00:12:35,071
Kind of tracking how far along we are in the entire game.

248
00:12:36,122 --> 00:12:41,687
And then we have the player who just brings primal emotions like fear, anger, and various other things into the experience.

249
00:12:42,508 --> 00:12:45,450
So character and player exist within the magic circle of the game, right?

250
00:12:45,490 --> 00:12:47,812
When we're playing the game, this is, that needs to be there.

251
00:12:48,213 --> 00:12:52,877
Then we also have the person who usually exists outside the magic circle.

252
00:12:52,997 --> 00:12:58,301
So we have the, um, we have the person as a player with a sense of skill level and reputation,

253
00:12:58,502 --> 00:13:01,064
but I don't want to talk too much about that, we're going to ignore that one.

254
00:13:01,823 --> 00:13:05,385
We do have a person who has a perceived sense of idealized self, right?

255
00:13:05,425 --> 00:13:07,707
We all like to see ourselves in a certain way.

256
00:13:07,747 --> 00:13:09,448
We all aspire to be somebody.

257
00:13:09,548 --> 00:13:13,250
So this is who we want to be or how we think other people perceive us.

258
00:13:13,791 --> 00:13:16,452
And of course, we do have the self as a person with life demands

259
00:13:16,512 --> 00:13:20,715
who has to catch the bus at 6 or various other things that just define our life.

260
00:13:21,956 --> 00:13:24,878
So we're going to ignore the person frame for the time being, right?

261
00:13:24,898 --> 00:13:27,279
I mean, this is double consciousness deconstructed, right?

262
00:13:27,299 --> 00:13:28,920
This is your player when he's playing the game.

263
00:13:29,441 --> 00:13:31,582
But because the person exists outside the magic circle.

264
00:13:31,924 --> 00:13:35,426
and it's going to make it a little bit more difficult to figure out the concepts and talk about them.

265
00:13:35,827 --> 00:13:37,888
We're just going to forget about them for the time being.

266
00:13:39,930 --> 00:13:43,933
So the concept behind the identity bubble is just reconciling those identity fragments.

267
00:13:44,033 --> 00:13:47,496
It's this idea that we can imagine identity in games as a bubble

268
00:13:47,896 --> 00:13:49,657
in which character and player follow along.

269
00:13:49,878 --> 00:13:55,282
And identity during play is maintained when the character and the player frames drift in the same direction, right?

270
00:13:55,682 --> 00:13:59,625
But as soon as one of them lags behind or starts floating in a completely different direction,

271
00:13:59,685 --> 00:14:01,407
the bubble pops and identity is lost.

272
00:14:02,924 --> 00:14:13,390
What's important to me is that this identity bubble needs to be maintained, because we have to do that both during runtime, right, we have to keep reinforcing identity as we're playing, but this also includes development.

273
00:14:13,950 --> 00:14:19,813
And to me, writing for games means cooperation between writer and designer for the entire duration of development.

274
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:31,519
We can actually see that right here in the bubble, because we have a representation for both the writer, right, he's down there, caring about the character, and for the game designers as well, who are up there and caring for, you know,

275
00:14:32,323 --> 00:14:33,544
the actual player experience.

276
00:14:34,144 --> 00:14:35,664
So this practice of hiring a writer

277
00:14:35,704 --> 00:14:37,505
towards the end of development just to write the story

278
00:14:37,545 --> 00:14:37,965
doesn't work.

279
00:14:39,205 --> 00:14:41,986
And more importantly, hiring a writer

280
00:14:42,046 --> 00:14:43,886
who doesn't understand player identity

281
00:14:44,206 --> 00:14:46,227
is going to open this huge can of worms.

282
00:14:46,607 --> 00:14:50,768
And well, hopefully you can use this talk to teach some people.

283
00:14:51,268 --> 00:14:54,189
So because I think in this room we all understand this.

284
00:14:54,269 --> 00:14:56,710
I mean, at least intuitively, but it doesn't really

285
00:14:56,770 --> 00:14:58,810
protect us from an executive coming in and having

286
00:14:58,830 --> 00:15:01,671
hired this famous comic writer, something like that.

287
00:15:01,751 --> 00:15:01,851
So.

288
00:15:02,452 --> 00:15:05,172
Every time that happens, we kind of need to figure out how to deal with that.

289
00:15:06,153 --> 00:15:09,754
And I think one way to actually do that, you know, if you are in this situation, is to

290
00:15:09,774 --> 00:15:14,755
just very quickly talk about what makes writing for games different from writing for other

291
00:15:14,775 --> 00:15:15,155
media.

292
00:15:15,495 --> 00:15:17,376
Like my high-level summary is actually very simple.

293
00:15:17,836 --> 00:15:20,816
Games are participatory, and movies and books are reflective.

294
00:15:21,537 --> 00:15:22,717
Let me show you what I mean by that.

295
00:15:25,518 --> 00:15:27,218
So this is linear media, right?

296
00:15:27,238 --> 00:15:27,958
This is a movie.

297
00:15:28,905 --> 00:15:31,906
In linear media, motivation is created in the character frame.

298
00:15:32,046 --> 00:15:33,127
Like it's created over there.

299
00:15:33,287 --> 00:15:34,587
I will take the ring tomorrow.

300
00:15:34,607 --> 00:15:37,028
This is propelling the entire experience forward.

301
00:15:37,608 --> 00:15:39,369
So now we have the player, which in this case,

302
00:15:39,409 --> 00:15:40,249
of course, is the viewer.

303
00:15:40,949 --> 00:15:42,970
And he's observing the character's actions on the screen.

304
00:15:43,390 --> 00:15:44,210
He's doing this right here.

305
00:15:44,250 --> 00:15:45,351
This is the reflective part.

306
00:15:45,671 --> 00:15:47,251
The viewer compares his own values,

307
00:15:47,271 --> 00:15:50,212
his own frame of reference to the depicted situation.

308
00:15:50,773 --> 00:15:53,794
So meaning emerges because the viewer

309
00:15:53,834 --> 00:15:56,194
is engaged in this internal dialogue about what's

310
00:15:56,214 --> 00:15:57,035
happening on the screen.

311
00:15:57,961 --> 00:16:00,302
Like in this case, he's edging Frodo on.

312
00:16:00,342 --> 00:16:01,022
Go Frodo!

313
00:16:01,282 --> 00:16:02,783
But he's also reflecting on himself.

314
00:16:02,843 --> 00:16:03,684
He's going, you know what?

315
00:16:03,744 --> 00:16:06,185
If I was a hobbit, I could do exactly the same thing.

316
00:16:06,245 --> 00:16:07,325
I wouldn't succumb to the ring.

317
00:16:07,705 --> 00:16:09,206
So it's kind of self-assuring.

318
00:16:09,406 --> 00:16:11,927
Or we're testing ourselves to see if what's going on

319
00:16:11,967 --> 00:16:13,648
on the screen would be true for us as well.

320
00:16:14,849 --> 00:16:16,309
This is actually very straightforward.

321
00:16:16,329 --> 00:16:18,090
If we're looking at the flow of consumption

322
00:16:18,110 --> 00:16:20,191
that's going on here, that's pretty straight.

323
00:16:20,251 --> 00:16:22,472
And we've mastered this over thousands of years.

324
00:16:23,052 --> 00:16:25,373
There's a bunch of experience, you know, like

325
00:16:25,972 --> 00:16:30,234
the never-ending story here, which played with this character-viewer relationship in kind of interesting ways, but

326
00:16:30,694 --> 00:16:33,174
ultimately, this experience is always reflective.

327
00:16:33,755 --> 00:16:35,895
That's awesome, except that games don't work that way.

328
00:16:36,055 --> 00:16:37,616
They actually work pretty much oppositely.

329
00:16:38,076 --> 00:16:39,236
Games are participatory.

330
00:16:39,756 --> 00:16:43,397
We're looking at motivation in games, well, it's created in the player, right over there.

331
00:16:43,417 --> 00:16:45,178
I mean, that's the reason we play games, right?

332
00:16:45,198 --> 00:16:46,558
We want to drive the action.

333
00:16:46,578 --> 00:16:47,619
We want to express ourselves.

334
00:16:47,979 --> 00:16:48,659
We want to lead.

335
00:16:49,646 --> 00:16:55,450
What becomes tricky is that now we want to use storylines and character motivation to fictionalize the player's goals.

336
00:16:55,470 --> 00:16:57,712
So all of a sudden we're creating motivation over here as well.

337
00:16:58,372 --> 00:17:01,754
So now the player starts reflecting on the character's actions until he realizes,

338
00:17:01,774 --> 00:17:05,037
well, wait a second, why am I reflecting actually on the character?

339
00:17:05,057 --> 00:17:07,038
So I don't know, what the fuck does that mean?

340
00:17:07,118 --> 00:17:11,661
So we have this duality, right, where motivation is created in one identity frame.

341
00:17:12,142 --> 00:17:15,084
There's a different identity frame we use to fictionalize this motivation.

342
00:17:15,764 --> 00:17:17,265
And we need to figure it out.

343
00:17:18,022 --> 00:17:20,383
So a result of this is a very confused player, right?

344
00:17:20,423 --> 00:17:21,384
And we've all been there.

345
00:17:21,424 --> 00:17:23,025
We've all had this nagging feeling of,

346
00:17:23,865 --> 00:17:24,866
why am I doing this again?

347
00:17:25,406 --> 00:17:26,707
It's this feeling of not really feeling

348
00:17:26,727 --> 00:17:27,987
like you're driving the action,

349
00:17:28,388 --> 00:17:29,408
of not really understanding

350
00:17:29,448 --> 00:17:30,929
why the character is doing something.

351
00:17:31,789 --> 00:17:33,790
Not really caring about the avatar's motivation.

352
00:17:34,891 --> 00:17:36,152
So there's actually a term for this,

353
00:17:37,332 --> 00:17:39,353
for this hollow feeling, this feeling of disconnect

354
00:17:39,493 --> 00:17:41,555
that Clint Hocking came up with a few years ago.

355
00:17:42,555 --> 00:17:44,776
I guess he's a kind of questionable character,

356
00:17:44,836 --> 00:17:45,677
the way I put this up.

357
00:17:47,003 --> 00:17:49,543
Clint called this feeling Lulu narrative dissonance.

358
00:17:50,003 --> 00:17:52,964
It came out of talking about Bioshock.

359
00:17:55,324 --> 00:17:58,685
So Lulu narrative dissonance is something that we as designers and writers create

360
00:17:59,205 --> 00:18:01,325
when we don't understand player identity.

361
00:18:01,585 --> 00:18:03,666
We open this rift between player and character

362
00:18:04,106 --> 00:18:05,946
and we don't even understand it's there

363
00:18:05,966 --> 00:18:07,467
and we don't know how to manage the problem.

364
00:18:07,947 --> 00:18:09,287
Because it is a manageable problem

365
00:18:09,367 --> 00:18:11,447
and that's what the identity bubble is about.

366
00:18:11,567 --> 00:18:13,528
It's just this expression of the problem.

367
00:18:13,568 --> 00:18:14,208
It's the idea that

368
00:18:14,517 --> 00:18:18,020
we have to keep all identity frames aligned by somehow hooking them together

369
00:18:18,380 --> 00:18:21,062
so they keep drifting in the same direction and keep the bubble from popping.

370
00:18:21,763 --> 00:18:24,965
And the way we do this is by controlling this identity gap,

371
00:18:25,146 --> 00:18:27,608
being aware of it and then doing something about it.

372
00:18:28,168 --> 00:18:31,271
So there's three examples of how this can be done that I want to look at.

373
00:18:31,291 --> 00:18:34,073
So there's us hooking them together.

374
00:18:35,715 --> 00:18:41,039
What's nice about it is that all three examples coincide with this identity range that we established earlier.

375
00:18:41,949 --> 00:18:45,211
What's important to know about this range is that it's completely analog, right?

376
00:18:45,271 --> 00:18:47,193
I mean, your approach might be wedged somewhere in the middle.

377
00:18:47,453 --> 00:18:49,935
You might not be making a pure puppet or pure vehicle game.

378
00:18:50,335 --> 00:18:54,037
You might be the poor crash test dummy, like somewhere right in the middle.

379
00:18:54,598 --> 00:18:56,439
But so the three approaches I want to talk about is

380
00:18:56,979 --> 00:19:00,081
to either create what I would call a Lulu narrative parity, right?

381
00:19:00,141 --> 00:19:01,182
Using a puppet avatar.

382
00:19:01,763 --> 00:19:05,345
We might be using a hybrid approach, using something like complementary goals,

383
00:19:05,385 --> 00:19:06,386
which goes somewhere in the middle.

384
00:19:07,228 --> 00:19:09,469
If you want to use a strongly characterized avatar,

385
00:19:09,849 --> 00:19:11,970
well, we might have to change the player's expectations

386
00:19:12,010 --> 00:19:13,551
of why he plays the game in the first place.

387
00:19:14,372 --> 00:19:16,092
And we do that using a mythic archetype.

388
00:19:17,073 --> 00:19:18,534
So I think the best way to talk about this

389
00:19:18,614 --> 00:19:21,615
is to just look at examples for each case here.

390
00:19:21,955 --> 00:19:23,756
And then once we're done, hopefully we

391
00:19:23,776 --> 00:19:26,198
can find some commonalities and then specific tools

392
00:19:26,258 --> 00:19:26,878
and takeaways.

393
00:19:32,081 --> 00:19:33,602
So we should start by looking at puppet games.

394
00:19:34,173 --> 00:19:38,277
Not this puppet game, unfortunately. It would be awesome talking about these kind of puppet games, right?

395
00:19:38,798 --> 00:19:44,003
The idea behind Ludo Narrative Parity is to align gameplay and story goals so closely

396
00:19:44,203 --> 00:19:47,346
that the player's agency is synonymous with the game's narrative progression.

397
00:19:48,007 --> 00:19:52,572
And anybody who's looked into this topic knows exactly which game I'm going to use now as an example.

398
00:19:52,812 --> 00:19:57,617
It's going to be Portal, because it's a great example of Ludo Narrative Parity.

399
00:19:58,463 --> 00:20:02,005
I'm not here to analyze Portal and how it creates gameplay per se, right?

400
00:20:02,125 --> 00:20:03,486
Countless people have done that before me.

401
00:20:03,526 --> 00:20:06,747
I just want to show how the game engages the different fragments of player identity.

402
00:20:07,608 --> 00:20:09,408
So this is me playing Portal, right?

403
00:20:09,468 --> 00:20:12,270
So, if I'm playing Portal, well, I want to get to GLaDOS, right?

404
00:20:12,310 --> 00:20:13,690
Because that means I've finished the game.

405
00:20:15,111 --> 00:20:17,272
I do that by finishing each test chamber, right?

406
00:20:17,332 --> 00:20:21,834
Which means solving all the puzzles in each chamber with the gameplay mechanisms provided to me.

407
00:20:23,155 --> 00:20:24,875
Now, for all of this, GLaDOS keeps talking to me.

408
00:20:24,895 --> 00:20:25,796
It keeps deriding me.

409
00:20:26,260 --> 00:20:31,622
creating a sense of anger and a sense of indignity as she talks to me, edging me on to get to the very end of this, and

410
00:20:31,642 --> 00:20:35,243
well, killing that computer bitch, right? Because she needs to die.

411
00:20:36,163 --> 00:20:38,484
So if we compare this to what the avatar wants to do,

412
00:20:39,004 --> 00:20:40,205
and her name is Chell, by the way,

413
00:20:40,545 --> 00:20:44,086
but that's not important. What's important is that you probably didn't know that, and

414
00:20:44,426 --> 00:20:45,707
her name isn't important, right?

415
00:20:46,187 --> 00:20:51,409
Well, Chell wants to get to GLaDOS because she wants to get out of this fucked-up situation that she's in, right?

416
00:20:51,889 --> 00:20:52,509
She wants to be free.

417
00:20:53,057 --> 00:20:58,840
So she does this by finishing each test chamber, which means solving all the puzzles in each chamber with the tools provided to her.

418
00:20:59,340 --> 00:21:04,383
And through all of this, GLaDOS keeps talking to her. She keeps deriding her, which reinforces this anger and this sense of indignity

419
00:21:05,303 --> 00:21:10,346
that's been inflicted through her capture, giving her the righteous fury to get to the end and kill that fucking computer bitch, right?

420
00:21:10,466 --> 00:21:14,588
So both examples are pretty much identical. They're remarkably similar.

421
00:21:15,648 --> 00:21:20,170
So in Portal, there's never an identity gap because the game maintains LULU narrative parity.

422
00:21:20,760 --> 00:21:25,741
What it means to play the game is exactly the same thing as what it means to be Chell in that situation.

423
00:21:28,902 --> 00:21:34,103
So a player and avatar are united in a situation where they're incarcerated by a sadistic computer, right?

424
00:21:34,203 --> 00:21:38,364
And they have this overwhelming urge to escape in the hope of sticking it to GLaDOS in the end.

425
00:21:39,464 --> 00:21:44,225
So the player knows exactly what it's like, what it means to be the avatar, what his or her motivation is,

426
00:21:44,325 --> 00:21:46,906
and how to act on that motivation. That's the important part right here.

427
00:21:47,602 --> 00:21:50,884
If we're looking at the identity bubble here, we see this ludonarrative parity, right?

428
00:21:50,904 --> 00:21:53,286
Because player and character are pulling each other along.

429
00:21:53,346 --> 00:21:57,569
Both identity frames are working towards exactly the same game, the same goals.

430
00:21:57,810 --> 00:22:00,852
So the bubble never pops, at least for me, and identity is strong.

431
00:22:01,893 --> 00:22:06,056
So fictionally, Chell is her own person, I guess, but in gameplay terms, she's identical to the player.

432
00:22:06,697 --> 00:22:08,578
If we are looking at the writing of Portal,

433
00:22:09,018 --> 00:22:13,062
doing the entire game, GLaDOS's commentaries, addressing player and character alike, right?

434
00:22:13,082 --> 00:22:13,742
There's no gap.

435
00:22:14,378 --> 00:22:22,564
And the brilliance of Portal's writing, beyond just having really good characterizations and all that stuff, is that it's constantly reminding the player of the shared situation, right?

436
00:22:22,684 --> 00:22:25,125
It's constantly keeping these identity frames aligned.

437
00:22:25,706 --> 00:22:35,132
Every time GLaDOS addresses Chell or the player or whatever, it reminds them that they're both the same, and it kind of starts hooking these frames together again, even though they might have drifted apart a little bit.

438
00:22:37,325 --> 00:22:43,007
So Lulu narrative parity works in Portal, I think mostly because it's based on primal motivation, right?

439
00:22:43,047 --> 00:22:45,948
It's something we inherently understand, something we don't like.

440
00:22:46,688 --> 00:22:50,429
There aren't even objectives in Portal, you know, GLaDOS talks at us, but mostly

441
00:22:50,930 --> 00:22:54,051
every goal in the game flows from this primal motivation of getting to the end.

442
00:22:54,511 --> 00:22:58,973
Things get a little bit trickier when we want to add external, like more nuanced motivation,

443
00:22:59,033 --> 00:23:00,073
something with bigger ideas.

444
00:23:00,653 --> 00:23:02,734
And if we want that to drive the story progression.

445
00:23:03,694 --> 00:23:06,435
Now we're talking about this duality that I talked about earlier, right?

446
00:23:06,990 --> 00:23:12,772
We motivate one identity frame with gameplay, but then another identity frame is used to contextualize that motivation somehow.

447
00:23:13,473 --> 00:23:16,154
So one way we can deal with this problem is complementary goals.

448
00:23:16,614 --> 00:23:19,616
We want to weave the player's identity into the core gameplay loop.

449
00:23:19,936 --> 00:23:22,557
And to me Fallout 3 is a great example of this.

450
00:23:23,297 --> 00:23:23,738
Fallout 3.

451
00:23:26,079 --> 00:23:28,960
In Fallout 3, the avatar, him or herself, is also an empty vessel.

452
00:23:29,200 --> 00:23:34,163
I think even more so than in Portal, because we can customize our avatar, right?

453
00:23:34,183 --> 00:23:35,563
Both statistically and visually.

454
00:23:36,455 --> 00:23:38,035
Portal's gameplay is driven by the player.

455
00:23:38,075 --> 00:23:40,735
It's his motivation to explore the world for resources.

456
00:23:40,755 --> 00:23:42,996
It's the joy of systemic advancement, which just means

457
00:23:43,156 --> 00:23:45,176
gaining levels and that kind of stuff.

458
00:23:45,776 --> 00:23:46,776
That's why we play the game.

459
00:23:47,217 --> 00:23:48,717
When we pick it up, that's what we expect.

460
00:23:49,197 --> 00:23:51,477
The problem is that this systemic exploration doesn't

461
00:23:51,497 --> 00:23:55,438
drive Fallout 3's story, because that goal is introduced

462
00:23:55,498 --> 00:23:57,158
externally over here in the character.

463
00:23:57,778 --> 00:24:01,039
As Fallout 3's pre-offered story goes, the avatar wants

464
00:24:01,079 --> 00:24:02,379
to find her dad.

465
00:24:03,139 --> 00:24:05,480
And once she's successful, she wants to help him on his

466
00:24:05,500 --> 00:24:05,960
quest to find his dad.

467
00:24:06,256 --> 00:24:07,756
to bring clean water to the wasteland.

468
00:24:09,777 --> 00:24:13,077
So this opens up this identity gap if we don't deal with it because those

469
00:24:13,637 --> 00:24:17,338
goals, they're not fundamentally derived from Fallout's gameplay mechanics.

