699
00:36:51,954 --> 00:36:54,576
or the rules underlying with just three screenshots,

700
00:36:54,956 --> 00:36:57,658
I could use Raiders of the Lost Ark and The Last Crusade.

701
00:36:59,641 --> 00:37:00,962
This is pretty much the story.

702
00:37:01,502 --> 00:37:02,823
So Uncharted 2 is a road movie.

703
00:37:03,044 --> 00:37:05,005
It's a story in which the journey is more important

704
00:37:05,025 --> 00:37:05,906
than the destination.

705
00:37:06,026 --> 00:37:08,007
And the fun thing is that it actually

706
00:37:08,027 --> 00:37:10,669
works in Uncharted 2's favor, because while the same goes

707
00:37:10,689 --> 00:37:12,730
for the gamer's agency expectations,

708
00:37:13,151 --> 00:37:14,572
the journey is probably more important

709
00:37:14,592 --> 00:37:15,692
than unlimited expression.

710
00:37:17,494 --> 00:37:19,255
So our mystic understanding of the story

711
00:37:19,335 --> 00:37:21,496
is the glue that's holding all of this stuff together.

712
00:37:22,337 --> 00:37:25,199
It buys us a bit of leeway, because the journey isn't

713
00:37:25,299 --> 00:37:27,561
actually quite as unpredictable and unexpected

714
00:37:27,641 --> 00:37:28,721
as we think it might be.

715
00:37:29,041 --> 00:37:31,242
I mean, we know we're going to get to Shambhala in the end, right?

716
00:37:31,282 --> 00:37:32,662
The question is, how do we get there?

717
00:37:33,282 --> 00:37:35,563
And in fact, the one time Identity didn't work for me,

718
00:37:35,583 --> 00:37:39,264
in Uncharted 2, is when Nathan Drake was trying to end the journey.

719
00:37:39,344 --> 00:37:41,204
He was like somewhere in the Himalayans and he's saying,

720
00:37:41,244 --> 00:37:42,065
you know, I've had enough.

721
00:37:42,485 --> 00:37:43,345
I knew that wasn't true.

722
00:37:43,385 --> 00:37:44,905
That was the one time it actually didn't work.

723
00:37:45,106 --> 00:37:48,607
So, on top of this, then Naughty Dog comes in

724
00:37:48,787 --> 00:37:51,047
and they invest an ungodly amount of attention

725
00:37:51,127 --> 00:37:53,028
to actually realign player and character as well.

726
00:37:53,829 --> 00:37:57,751
I think one of them is what Naughty Dog called the gap in one of those talks.

727
00:37:57,891 --> 00:38:02,693
It's this idea that for each unexpected obstacle that we're throwing in the player's way,

728
00:38:03,733 --> 00:38:05,754
well, it wipes out all the information about the journey.

729
00:38:05,854 --> 00:38:06,955
It levels the playing field.

730
00:38:06,975 --> 00:38:09,376
It actually puts player and character on the same page,

731
00:38:09,436 --> 00:38:12,277
because the information of what's ahead is actually wiped out.

732
00:38:12,937 --> 00:38:16,119
The other thing they do is that when Nathan Drake does set a direction,

733
00:38:16,159 --> 00:38:18,840
like he says, we have to go over there, it's always tied to a landmark.

734
00:38:18,880 --> 00:38:20,801
So now the player can dig his teeth into that.

735
00:38:21,194 --> 00:38:25,017
he can drive the action towards that landmark because he knows exactly where he's going.

736
00:38:27,779 --> 00:38:31,802
So all of this already brings character and player closely together, but it's very low

737
00:38:31,842 --> 00:38:32,362
frequency.

738
00:38:32,402 --> 00:38:35,984
It only happens like every 30 seconds or 30 minutes or something like that, right?

739
00:38:36,505 --> 00:38:37,485
So we need to do even more.

740
00:38:39,427 --> 00:38:41,869
And this is very similar to what we saw in Fallout 3.

741
00:38:42,249 --> 00:38:46,292
We also have to hook character and player together by fundamentally weaving the character's

742
00:38:46,352 --> 00:38:49,714
identity into what it means to play the game, into the core gameplay actions.

743
00:38:52,042 --> 00:38:53,822
So Nathan Drake is a treasure hunter at heart, right?

744
00:38:53,842 --> 00:38:55,822
The player acts out this character trait

745
00:38:55,842 --> 00:38:57,763
by searching for hidden treasure all over the place.

746
00:38:59,023 --> 00:38:59,723
Drake is clever.

747
00:38:59,823 --> 00:39:03,164
He has a knack for unraveling historic mysteries.

748
00:39:03,224 --> 00:39:05,024
And this is a trait that we act out as the player

749
00:39:05,044 --> 00:39:06,204
when we're solving all these puzzles.

750
00:39:06,704 --> 00:39:09,105
Now he's doing it, but we're doing it with him.

751
00:39:09,605 --> 00:39:11,205
And finally, Drake is very resourceful.

752
00:39:11,545 --> 00:39:13,305
And I think that's fundamentally woven

753
00:39:13,325 --> 00:39:14,646
into the game's traversal gameplay.

754
00:39:14,686 --> 00:39:16,346
Because we always get around situations

755
00:39:16,386 --> 00:39:17,746
nobody else was able to pass.

756
00:39:18,186 --> 00:39:20,147
We always find the most clever way to get somewhere.

757
00:39:21,103 --> 00:39:26,146
On a base level, Unshuttered 2's gameplay actions are all geared towards reinforcing Nathan Drake's character, right?

758
00:39:26,286 --> 00:39:29,808
And they're all geared towards making this guy very happy.

759
00:39:30,188 --> 00:39:33,849
Like, when the player plays this game, he knows what it's like to be Drake.

760
00:39:33,869 --> 00:39:36,491
He almost feels like he's Nathan Drake, which is what he came for.

761
00:39:37,191 --> 00:39:39,772
So there's a very high level of identification here, but...

762
00:39:40,332 --> 00:39:45,075
Well, identification isn't a great term, because I don't think it quite expresses what it means to play this game.

763
00:39:45,615 --> 00:39:47,916
What I want to call it instead is identity absorption.

764
00:39:48,913 --> 00:39:51,814
And this is a term that's coming from Understanding Comics.

765
00:39:52,295 --> 00:39:55,195
It's a concept where Scott McCloud talks about the fact

766
00:39:55,215 --> 00:39:56,936
that when we're driving a car, we always

767
00:39:56,976 --> 00:39:58,557
remain a separate entity from the car,

768
00:39:58,597 --> 00:40:00,077
and we understand that, right?

769
00:40:00,517 --> 00:40:03,878
But we often become so immersed in the driving experience

770
00:40:03,918 --> 00:40:05,719
that we start talking about the car in first person.

771
00:40:05,759 --> 00:40:07,339
We start saying, oh my god, he hit me.

772
00:40:07,779 --> 00:40:09,240
He's cutting me off.

773
00:40:09,800 --> 00:40:10,320
Well, guess what?

774
00:40:10,480 --> 00:40:12,181
Nathan Drake is a vehicle, right?

775
00:40:12,201 --> 00:40:12,741
He's a car.

776
00:40:12,801 --> 00:40:15,162
So I think exactly the same thing is happening right here.

777
00:40:15,602 --> 00:40:18,443
We don't become Nathan Drake, but we absorb his identity.

778
00:40:19,376 --> 00:40:23,757
I think that's a good explanation of how we actually relate to a very strongly characterized avatar like this.

779
00:40:23,897 --> 00:40:27,517
If I had to state the design goals for both of these identity approaches,

780
00:40:28,418 --> 00:40:31,278
I would say that puppet avatars are about creating high agency,

781
00:40:31,978 --> 00:40:34,759
and vehicle avatars are about creating high identity absorption.

782
00:40:35,139 --> 00:40:36,859
And that's the reason why Unshuttered 2 works.

783
00:40:38,460 --> 00:40:42,340
Alright. So, I hope these have been very divergent examples, right,

784
00:40:42,400 --> 00:40:44,041
of how we're actually creating player identity.

785
00:40:44,061 --> 00:40:46,781
And hopefully you've seen the underlying identity concepts,

786
00:40:46,801 --> 00:40:49,102
the double consciousness, and all that stuff shine through.

787
00:40:49,995 --> 00:40:53,918
So I want to finish this talk by just looking at some advice, some things that we can come

788
00:40:54,779 --> 00:40:55,459
take away from this.

789
00:40:56,480 --> 00:40:59,983
So before you're even writing the story, just ask yourself the question, what does it mean

790
00:41:00,023 --> 00:41:00,464
to be X?

791
00:41:00,484 --> 00:41:01,925
What does it mean to be this character?

792
00:41:02,505 --> 00:41:06,268
And then try to fundamentally express that identity in gameplay.

793
00:41:07,349 --> 00:41:11,793
Because this way, like this feeling of character is constantly reinforced because the player's

794
00:41:11,813 --> 00:41:13,695
gameplay actions keep

795
00:41:14,244 --> 00:41:16,165
well, I keep aligning these two consciousness, right?

796
00:41:16,185 --> 00:41:18,447
I mean, this is not something where we just establish a hook

797
00:41:18,487 --> 00:41:20,729
between two identity frames and then they stay hooked together.

798
00:41:20,809 --> 00:41:22,230
These are impulses that we send.

799
00:41:22,731 --> 00:41:24,973
Those frames are always going to slowly drift apart,

800
00:41:24,993 --> 00:41:27,154
so we have to keep sending these little impulses that

801
00:41:27,214 --> 00:41:28,355
keep hooking them back together.

802
00:41:28,996 --> 00:41:31,618
And if your character identity is fundamentally

803
00:41:31,718 --> 00:41:32,919
anchored in the gameplay actions,

804
00:41:32,959 --> 00:41:34,961
you just keep doing this at a very high frequency.

805
00:41:36,842 --> 00:41:38,664
Just to show you how important this concept is,

806
00:41:38,704 --> 00:41:39,885
I want to look at Bioshock 2.

807
00:41:40,325 --> 00:41:42,827
So this is my disclaimer that I really like Bioshock 2,

808
00:41:43,308 --> 00:41:43,548
but.

809
00:41:44,794 --> 00:41:50,137
this is the one game, or, this was an awesome game, but it had a really bad feeling of player identity.

810
00:41:50,177 --> 00:41:55,119
Because, well, Bioshock 2 puts me into the role of a rogue big daddy, right?

811
00:41:55,159 --> 00:42:02,843
So, I played Bioshock 1, and I have a very, very clearly and narrowly defined idea of what big daddy stands for.

812
00:42:02,883 --> 00:42:05,264
That he's badass protectors of those little girls.

813
00:42:05,684 --> 00:42:08,825
And then Bioshock 2 comes along, and it's very schizophrenic on its archetype.

814
00:42:09,409 --> 00:42:12,732
On the one hand, many of the core gameplay actions treat me like I'm a human player.

815
00:42:12,752 --> 00:42:16,475
I'm eating fucking cream cakes and drinking coffee and I don't even know how.

816
00:42:16,515 --> 00:42:17,676
Does it go through the helmet?

817
00:42:17,996 --> 00:42:19,057
To replenish my health.

818
00:42:19,658 --> 00:42:23,661
On the other hand, the game is expecting me to feel and sometimes act like a big daddy.

819
00:42:23,681 --> 00:42:27,544
That's the overriding motivation, actually, to get to the end of the story.

820
00:42:28,125 --> 00:42:31,187
But then it presents with the choice of being able to harvest the little sisters, which

821
00:42:31,267 --> 00:42:33,169
once again is completely out of character.

822
00:42:33,269 --> 00:42:37,993
So as I'm playing Mirror Shock 2, I have this really inconclusive treatment.

823
00:42:38,598 --> 00:42:42,722
of the character's identity, and I think it starts like pricking needles into the identity

824
00:42:42,742 --> 00:42:44,184
bubble at a very high frequency.

825
00:42:45,004 --> 00:42:51,091
Because the moment-to-moment gameplay is communicating one thing, but then the overall story is

826
00:42:51,151 --> 00:42:54,454
communicating a completely different direction of what the character is about.

827
00:42:55,115 --> 00:42:59,199
So every time I eat a cream cake or harvest a little sister, character and player start

828
00:42:59,219 --> 00:43:00,660
just drifting apart a little bit more.

829
00:43:02,473 --> 00:43:07,356
Microshock 2 was awesome, but I think like at the third level or so, it had lost all sense of identity for me,

830
00:43:07,456 --> 00:43:09,658
because I didn't know what it meant to be a big daddy.

831
00:43:11,339 --> 00:43:14,902
The main lesson I want you to take away from this is just this understanding of double consciousness,

832
00:43:15,182 --> 00:43:17,243
like with the character, player, and person model,

833
00:43:17,864 --> 00:43:22,807
and Harvey Smith's identity frames, which then form each identity fragments, which form each of this frame.

834
00:43:23,347 --> 00:43:30,052
So I think most of bad game writing, 99% whatever, can be traced back to just treating games like we're writing for other media.

835
00:43:30,580 --> 00:43:33,481
So hopefully you're able to explain to people why you shouldn't be doing that.

836
00:43:35,202 --> 00:43:39,083
And then I just hope to have imparted some concepts, some language we can use to come

837
00:43:39,123 --> 00:43:42,484
back and actually talk about games and about identity approaches.

838
00:43:43,024 --> 00:43:49,106
If you know about this identity range, well, you can actually see where the games we talked

839
00:43:49,146 --> 00:43:50,847
about fall on this identity range, right?

840
00:43:51,087 --> 00:43:55,708
And there's a bunch more examples, which all just kind of show you where they belong.

841
00:43:56,233 --> 00:43:59,895
We can even use it to show how the approach changed between different games.

842
00:44:00,095 --> 00:44:01,996
Like the last game I worked on is Dead Space 2.

843
00:44:02,056 --> 00:44:04,758
Well, Dead Space 1 is very much on the left side.

844
00:44:04,778 --> 00:44:10,681
Dead Space 2 comes along, adds a voice, it adds a lot of cutscenes and that kind of stuff to Isaac Clarke,

845
00:44:10,761 --> 00:44:12,762
and it falls much more into the vehicle category.

846
00:44:13,002 --> 00:44:17,764
Resistance was very similar, where the approach changed between game 1 and 2, and we added a voice.

847
00:44:18,843 --> 00:44:21,004
And all of this has been very much about action games, right?

848
00:44:21,024 --> 00:44:22,084
Because that's what I work on.

849
00:44:22,204 --> 00:44:24,025
You can actually use it for other genres as well,

850
00:44:24,065 --> 00:44:24,666
like rock band.

851
00:44:24,766 --> 00:44:26,186
Like the main rock band experience

852
00:44:26,206 --> 00:44:27,907
is all about building your own rock hood.

853
00:44:28,427 --> 00:44:30,628
But rock band's Beatles is all about reliving

854
00:44:30,688 --> 00:44:31,709
somebody else's journey.

855
00:44:31,769 --> 00:44:32,990
It's the vehicle rock band.

856
00:44:33,670 --> 00:44:36,391
And I know Guitar Hero is dead now,

857
00:44:36,551 --> 00:44:39,573
but there's even a distinction right there between rock band

858
00:44:39,613 --> 00:44:40,373
and Guitar Hero.

859
00:44:40,433 --> 00:44:43,675
Because, well, Guitar Hero was always about.

860
00:44:44,084 --> 00:44:48,066
we're living like collecting all of these rock stars and playing as them, right?

861
00:44:48,086 --> 00:44:49,387
So that's where the difference was there.

862
00:44:51,608 --> 00:44:55,350
So we can create a similar chart for the mythic quality of various games, right?

863
00:44:55,450 --> 00:44:57,711
Myth-building, myth-creation, and myth-recalling.

864
00:44:57,851 --> 00:45:02,734
Once again, we got those games that we talked about in this talk, and there's a whole bunch

865
00:45:02,774 --> 00:45:04,875
of other games that fall into the spectrum as well.

866
00:45:06,996 --> 00:45:10,438
So if you've been tasked with coming up with a story, a character for a game,

867
00:45:11,068 --> 00:45:14,229
Here's some quick closing thoughts on that. Figure out what kind of game you're making.

868
00:45:14,990 --> 00:45:18,431
Are you making a puppet game? Are you making a vehicle game? Are you making something in between?

869
00:45:18,591 --> 00:45:24,854
All approaches are valid. I subscribe to a certain philosophy, but, you know, in the industry, all of these approaches are valid.

870
00:45:25,474 --> 00:45:28,255
But they're going to guide what you should and shouldn't do, and you need to understand this.

871
00:45:28,375 --> 00:45:32,837
If you're going to make a puppet game, it might be non-linear. It's going to have an emphasis on the player story.

872
00:45:33,318 --> 00:45:36,699
It's going to be about the player allowing, like, building his own myth.

873
00:45:37,345 --> 00:45:42,769
There might not be cutscenes because I think that would take away control from the player and it's very much against that concept.

874
00:45:43,710 --> 00:45:49,834
If you're making a vehicle game, well it's probably going to be highly structured and it's going to be linear and it's going to have an emphasis on with recall.

875
00:45:50,194 --> 00:45:57,799
You might be able to use cutscenes, you probably can, you can use pre-offered character traits and you can use those traits to propel the story forward.

876
00:45:58,719 --> 00:46:03,443
So I think puppet games are easier generally when it comes to just the identity approach.

877
00:46:03,463 --> 00:46:05,304
They're going to be much harder on various other levels.

878
00:46:06,337 --> 00:46:08,938
So if you are making a vehicle game, be very careful.

879
00:46:08,978 --> 00:46:11,679
Be 100% sure you understand what you're getting yourself into.

880
00:46:11,699 --> 00:46:15,200
Because I've kind of danced around the issue, but if you are making a vehicle game,

881
00:46:15,600 --> 00:46:17,341
you're making a fucking talking car, right?

882
00:46:17,941 --> 00:46:21,703
And those talking cars might have been awesome in the 80s, especially where I come from, but...

883
00:46:21,723 --> 00:46:26,925
you know, they can be annoying. They can even be completely unnecessary, right?

884
00:46:27,605 --> 00:46:29,026
I mean, just imagine you're driving down Highway 1,

885
00:46:29,386 --> 00:46:32,887
and you're witnessing this beautiful sunset over the Pacific Ocean.

886
00:46:32,907 --> 00:46:34,308
You're just sitting there, you're appreciating,

887
00:46:34,328 --> 00:46:36,048
and then all of a sudden, you hear this voice saying...

888
00:46:36,927 --> 00:46:38,388
Ah, look at that beautiful sunset.

889
00:46:38,428 --> 00:46:40,729
And you realize, fuck, I'm sitting in my car.

890
00:46:40,769 --> 00:46:41,989
My car is talking to me.

891
00:46:42,549 --> 00:46:44,910
And I'm not sure if this remark really enhanced the moment.

892
00:46:45,410 --> 00:46:49,252
I mean, it should probably be appreciated and experienced

893
00:46:49,272 --> 00:46:50,292
in quite appreciation.

894
00:46:50,332 --> 00:46:52,233
So you can do this, of course.

895
00:46:52,293 --> 00:46:54,134
I mean, this is a very personal decision.

896
00:46:54,174 --> 00:46:57,095
I'm just trying to point out that every time the character

897
00:46:57,195 --> 00:46:59,736
expresses a sentiment and that's not shared by the player,

898
00:46:59,936 --> 00:47:01,396
well, you're widening the identity gap.

899
00:47:01,977 --> 00:47:03,217
You're making them drift apart.

900
00:47:07,326 --> 00:47:09,667
So finally, understand the underlying myth of the game.

901
00:47:09,907 --> 00:47:11,468
And this is especially important when you're

902
00:47:11,488 --> 00:47:13,849
creating a story-driven game, like with a vehicle character.

903
00:47:13,889 --> 00:47:14,830
It's actually imperative.

904
00:47:15,350 --> 00:47:17,531
So you must identify and execute on a myth

905
00:47:17,731 --> 00:47:20,212
that the game will be based on, or it's going to feel aimless.

906
00:47:20,573 --> 00:47:22,254
The player won't really know where it's going,

907
00:47:22,314 --> 00:47:23,234
and it's going to feel hollow.

908
00:47:23,694 --> 00:47:25,715
And of course, this lecture can dive into the subject.

909
00:47:25,755 --> 00:47:26,716
We're pretty much done now.

910
00:47:26,756 --> 00:47:28,737
But if you are looking for some further reading,

911
00:47:28,877 --> 00:47:31,238
I suggest the late Blake Snyder's book,

912
00:47:31,278 --> 00:47:34,480
Save the Cat Goes to the Movie, which I think the Unshutter 2

913
00:47:34,920 --> 00:47:35,640
team used as well.

914
00:47:37,158 --> 00:47:42,200
So, both types, myth-building games like Fallout, right, or myth-recalling experiences like

915
00:47:42,280 --> 00:47:45,761
Uncharted have merit, and I think players seek them out equally, but for completely

916
00:47:45,801 --> 00:47:46,341
different reasons.

917
00:47:46,902 --> 00:47:50,463
So as a designer, you need to understand the distinction between those types, and then

918
00:47:50,583 --> 00:47:52,864
take the differences into account when you're designing a game.

919
00:47:54,184 --> 00:47:56,765
But when it comes to myth reinforcement, I really believe in that, right?

920
00:47:56,805 --> 00:48:01,027
And I believe in that because I'm a game designer, and game design is kind of a black art.

921
00:48:01,467 --> 00:48:04,588
There aren't very many fundamental facts that I can hang my head on.

922
00:48:05,022 --> 00:48:09,804
It's up to all of us here to come up with our own belief systems about what makes games work and what doesn't work.

923
00:48:10,305 --> 00:48:15,588
Then we might even go out and we're looking, we're perusing the media landscape, we're finding various psychological tests,

924
00:48:16,128 --> 00:48:18,429
texts because, you know, we want to reinforce that belief.

925
00:48:18,469 --> 00:48:23,352
We might come to specific GDC talks because, you know what, if they tell us what we believe in,

926
00:48:23,952 --> 00:48:26,794
it's very comforting to know that you can trust in your own beliefs.

